  Q1) Dependency Version management of libraries (Spring dependency management for gradle? What is for kotlin?)
  Q2) Explain: version-catalog key can't be both a leaf value and a namespace prefix for another dashed key
  Q3) What is version-catalog key ?

  ---

  A1) The Spring side uses the `io.spring.dependency-management` Gradle plugin (alias
  `spring-dependency-management` in this project's libs.versions.toml, applied wherever
  spring-boot is applied). It imports Spring's BOM (bill-of-materials) so you can declare
  `implementation("org.springframework:spring-web")` without a version — the BOM pins it.
  It's Spring-specific and only manages Spring-published/managed coordinates.

  Kotlin itself has no equivalent "dependency management" plugin — Kotlin projects use
  Gradle's own native mechanism instead: Version Catalogs (gradle/libs.versions.toml),
  which is exactly what this project already does. It's not tied to Spring or Kotlin, it's
  a Gradle feature: a single TOML file declares versions/libraries/plugins/bundles once,
  and every module references them via generated type-safe accessors (e.g.
  `libs.grpc.kotlin.stub`, `libs.plugins.kotlin.jvm`). For BOM-style "one version pins many
  artifacts" behavior outside Spring (e.g. for grpc or protobuf), you'd use Gradle's
  `java-platform` plugin or import a third-party BOM with `implementation(platform(...))` —
  the catalog and platforms complement each other rather than compete.

  A2) Gradle turns every catalog key into a chain of accessor properties by splitting on
  `-` (and `_`/`.`). So a library key `grpc-kotlin-stub` becomes `libs.grpc.kotlin.stub`,
  where `grpc` and `grpc.kotlin` become synthetic namespace objects along the way, not
  real values.

  The conflict described happens when one key is a *complete* alias (a leaf/value) and
  another key uses that same alias as a *prefix* segment. Example: if this catalog defined
  both a library called `grpc` (so `libs.grpc` should resolve to a dependency notation) and
  a library called `grpc-stub` (so `libs.grpc` must also be a namespace holding `.stub`),
  Gradle can't generate `libs.grpc` as both a leaf property and a container object at once
  — it fails catalog validation with an error like "... cannot be both a value and a prefix
  for other dashed names". Looking at the actual libs.versions.toml here, this is why there
  is no bare `grpc` key — only prefixed ones (`grpc-kotlin-stub`, `grpc-protobuf`,
  `grpc-stub`, `grpc-netty`, `grpc-services`, and the versions `grpc-java`/`grpc-kotlin`) —
  so the current catalog is safe. It would only break if someone later added a plain
  `grpc = "..."` alias.

  A3) A version-catalog key (alias) is the name you give an entry inside one of the four
  tables in libs.versions.toml — `[versions]`, `[libraries]`, `[bundles]`, `[plugins]` —
  e.g. `kotlin`, `spring-boot`, `grpc-kotlin-stub` in this project's catalog. Gradle uses
  the key both as the lookup name in the TOML and as the basis for the generated
  type-safe Kotlin DSL accessor (`libs.versions.kotlin`, `libs.spring.boot`,
  `libs.grpc.kotlin.stub`), converting dash/underscore/dot separators into nested
  `.` property access. Valid keys must match `[a-zA-Z]([a-zA-Z0-9_.-])+`. Because the key
  doubles as an accessor path, its structure is what creates the leaf-vs-prefix collision
  described in Q2/A2.
